  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Money Laundering Suppression Act of 1994\n\n2. Key Provisions:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Money laundering criminal offenses)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Monetary transactions in criminally derived property)\n\n3. Regulatory Agencies Involved:\n- Financial Crimes Enforcement Network (FinCEN)\n- Internal Revenue Service (IRS)\n- Department of Justice (DOJ)\n\n4. Key Requirements:\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Implementing anti-money laundering (AML) programs\n- Maintaining transaction records\n- Conducting customer due diligence\n\n5. Penalties:\n- Significant fines\n- Potential imprisonment\n- Asset forfeiture\n\nThese statutes provide comprehensive legal frameworks for preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities across various financial sectors.",
